1Ô∏è‚É£ Tell me about a high-impact technical problem you solved

"In one of my recent projects, users were manually entering account and routing numbers for one-time payments, which often caused errors. My task was to reduce these errors and improve customer trust. I led the integration with ChasePayByBank APIs to validate credentials automatically. I coordinated with the vendor to understand the API flows, implemented the UI enhancements using React.js to give real-time feedback to users, and enabled webhook APIs via Apigee for backend communication. I also coordinated across multiple teams to ensure end-to-end enablement. As a result, payment entry errors dropped significantly, and the customer experience improved, building trust in our one-time payment flow."

2Ô∏è‚É£ Tell me about a time a project didn‚Äôt go as planned

"During the PayPal Braintree migration, the existing vendor system was sunsetting faster than expected, which could have caused disruption in payment processing. I led discussions with the vendor and internal teams to map dependencies, created detailed test cases to validate end-to-end transactions, and implemented the migration to Braintree while maintaining backward compatibility. We successfully completed the migration without downtime, ensuring seamless transactions for customers and mitigating vendor sunset risks."

3Ô∏è‚É£ How do you handle conflicts with teammates or stakeholders

"I approach conflicts by listening to all viewpoints and gathering facts before making decisions. For example, during ChasePayByBank integration, there was a disagreement between teams on API deadlines. I organized a technical discussion, clarified dependencies, and aligned timelines. This way, we avoided delays, ensured smooth integration, and resolved conflicts professionally without blame."

4Ô∏è‚É£ How do you prioritize tasks when everything is urgent

"I prioritize based on business impact and dependencies. For instance, while working on parallel payment initiatives, validating ChasePayByBank credentials was critical to reducing errors, so I prioritized it over UI enhancements, which were important but less urgent. This ensures critical features are delivered first while maintaining overall project quality."

5Ô∏è‚É£ How did you design the batch/system processing (1M records)

"For large-scale batch processing, we partitioned data into smaller batches to process independently. Each Kubernetes pod handled a batch, using thread pools matching CPU cores for parallel execution. For payment API validations like ChasePayByBank, we respected API rate limits and implemented retries with a dead-letter queue for failed records. Monitoring dashboards provided real-time visibility into batch processing. Horizontal scaling of pods handled increased loads, while vertical scaling improved per-pod processing speed. This approach ensured reliable, scalable, and error-resilient processing of large datasets."

6Ô∏è‚É£ How do you ensure high-quality integration with external APIs

"We started with vendor discussions to understand API contracts. Then, we implemented input validation, error handling, and webhook APIs using Apigee. We built unit and integration tests to simulate API failures and monitored API latency and errors. For ChasePayByBank, this reduced errors from manual inputs and improved reliability, while the PayPal Braintree migration maintained uninterrupted payment processing."

7Ô∏è‚É£ How do you handle retries and failures

"For individual record failures, we log to a dead-letter queue and retry asynchronously. For batch failures, pods retry with exponential backoff, and persistent failures are reviewed manually. If a pod or node crashes, batch states are tracked in the database so other pods can reclaim unprocessed batches. All processing is designed to be idempotent, ensuring no duplicate transactions or data corruption."

8Ô∏è‚É£ How do pods, CPU cores, and scaling work in AWS/Kubernetes

"Pods are scheduled onto EC2 nodes, which have physical CPU cores. Each pod has CPU requests and limits. Java inside the pod sees only the allocated cores, which determines how many threads we can run in parallel. Horizontal scaling adds more pods to increase throughput, while vertical scaling increases CPU or memory per pod. In the payment system, multiple pods validate credentials concurrently while respecting API limits, and autoscaling ensures pods scale automatically if load spikes."

9Ô∏è‚É£ How do you mentor junior developers

"I conduct code reviews, share best practices, and guide juniors on system design decisions. For example, during microservices development for payments, I helped junior developers understand asynchronous API integration and webhook handling. This improved their skills, reduced errors, and increased overall team productivity."

üîü How do you communicate technical issues to non-technical stakeholders

"I use visual diagrams, dashboards, and simplified explanations. For example, I explained the ChasePayByBank API flow to the product team using sequence diagrams, showing how automatic validation reduces errors without exposing backend complexity. This ensures stakeholders understand the value and impact of technical solutions."

11Ô∏è‚É£ System Design / Technical Summary (Can be spoken if asked for your approach)

"For payments, we worked on two critical initiatives in parallel: ChasePayByBank integration and PayPal Braintree migration. The ChasePayByBank integration reduces user entry errors by validating credentials via APIs, with webhook support for backend updates and rich UI feedback. The Braintree migration replaced a sunsetting vendor to maintain reliable payment processing. We built a monitoring platform for real-time and historical visibility. Scaling is handled through Kubernetes pods with CPU-based thread pools, retries and dead-letter queues ensure reliability, and horizontal/vertical scaling supports throughput and speed requirements. All of this improved customer trust and transaction reliability."

‚úÖ Tips for Delivery

Speak confidently ‚Äî use natural pauses, don‚Äôt rush.

Highlight results ‚Äî always quantify where possible (error reduction, uptime, customer satisfaction).

Use ‚ÄúI did‚Äù instead of ‚Äúwe did‚Äù for leadership questions.

Be ready for follow-up questions ‚Äî HM may ask: ‚ÄúHow did you decide thread pool size?‚Äù or ‚ÄúWhat monitoring metrics did you track?‚Äù
